<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="57" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,266,1092]" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stichel. The" authorityYear="1902" box="[151,375,266,291]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haenschi">
<emphasis box="[151,375,266,291]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Brassolis haenschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a rare, high-altitude (
<quantity box="[677,823,266,292]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.45" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" unit="m" value="1450.0" valueMax="2000.0" valueMin="900.0">900–2000m</quantity>
), species known so far only in the central eastern Andes in 
<collectingCountry box="[268,365,306,332]" name="Ecuador" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
(nominate 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stichel. The" authorityYear="1902" box="[503,607,306,331]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haenschi">
<emphasis box="[503,607,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">haenschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), central 
<collectingCountry box="[723,777,306,332]" name="Peru" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Peru</collectingCountry>
(
<emphasis box="[796,811,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">h</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[828,939,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">rufescens</emphasis>
Rothschild) and 
<collectingCountry box="[1146,1266,306,332]" name="Venezuela" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
(
<emphasis box="[1285,1436,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">h. maritimus</emphasis>
Stichel). At times, all three taxa have been regarded as subspecies of 
<taxonomicName authority="Godart [1824]" authorityName="Godart" authorityYear="1824" box="[954,1200,346,372]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="astyra">
<emphasis box="[954,1027,346,371]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">astyra</emphasis>
Godart [1824]
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Fruhstorfer, H." box="[1215,1431,346,372]" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" pagination="285 - 332" refId="ref5981" refString="Fruhstorfer, H. (1912 b) Family Brassolidae. Pages 285 - 332 In: Seitz A. (ed.), The Macrolepidoptera of the World, vol. 2. Stuttgart: Alfred Kernen Verlag." type="book chapter" year="1912">Fruhstorfer 1912b</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Rothschild, L. W." box="[151,347,386,412]" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" pagination="299 - 318" refId="ref6053" refString="Rothschild, L. W. (1916) Notes on Amathusiidae, Brassolidae, Morphidae, etc, with descriptions of new forms. Novitates Zoologicae, 23, 299 - 318." type="journal article" year="1916">Rothschild 1916</bibRefCitation>
) or even 
<taxonomicName authority="(Racheli and Racheli 2001)" baseAuthorityName="Racheli and Racheli" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[461,909,386,412]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sophorae">
<emphasis box="[461,570,386,411]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">sophorae</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Racheli, R. &amp; Racheli, T." box="[587,900,386,412]" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" pagination="213 - 380" refId="ref6022" refString="Racheli, R. &amp; Racheli, T. (2001) An annotated list of Ecuadorian butterflies. Fragmenta entomologica (Rome), 33, 213 - 380." type="journal article" year="2001">Racheli and Racheli 2001</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Carla Penz (
<emphasis box="[1070,1229,386,411]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">pers. commn.</emphasis>
) informs me that the male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stichel. The" authorityYear="1902" box="[398,502,426,451]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haenschi">
<emphasis box="[398,502,426,451]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">haenschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Godart" authorityYear="1824" box="[569,642,426,451]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="astyra">
<emphasis box="[569,642,426,451]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">astyra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) show a few, slight, differences from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Racheli and Racheli" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[1086,1195,426,451]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sophorae">
<emphasis box="[1086,1195,426,451]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">sophorae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1864" box="[1252,1338,426,451]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="isthmia">
<emphasis box="[1252,1338,426,451]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">isthmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,266,1092]" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">
Male 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stichel. The" authorityYear="1902" box="[265,369,466,491]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haenschi">
<emphasis box="[265,369,466,491]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">haenschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1864" box="[579,665,466,491]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="isthmia">
<emphasis box="[579,665,466,491]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">isthmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Racheli and Racheli" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[721,830,466,491]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sophorae">
<emphasis box="[721,830,466,491]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">sophorae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The main difference from these taxa is in the ocelli on the hindwing underside (particularly the lower one). In both sexes of the three 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stichel. The" authorityYear="1902" box="[1148,1252,506,531]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haenschi">
<emphasis box="[1148,1252,506,531]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">haenschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taxa examined (
<emphasis box="[161,272,546,571]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">rufescens</emphasis>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[344,401,546,572]" name="Peru" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Peru</collectingCountry>
, nominate 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stichel. The" authorityYear="1902" box="[531,635,546,571]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haenschi">
<emphasis box="[531,635,546,571]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">haenschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[708,807,546,572]" name="Ecuador" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, and 
<emphasis box="[870,989,546,571]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">maritimus</emphasis>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[1063,1188,546,572]" name="Venezuela" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
), the hindwing ocelli lack the narrow, dark brown, border seen in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1864" box="[682,768,586,611]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="isthmia">
<emphasis box="[682,768,586,611]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">isthmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[828,945,586,611]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Racheli and Racheli" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[828,941,586,611]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sophorae">sophorae</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Additionally, on the forewing underside, the two very narrow submarginal bands which occur in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1864" box="[800,886,626,651]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="isthmia">
<emphasis box="[800,886,626,651]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">isthmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(very clear on 
<figureCitation box="[1062,1144,626,652]" captionStart="PLATE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,238,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-116@9.[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="PLATE 3 (details). 1,2. Brassolis granadensis female, COLOMBIA: Otanche, JFL. 3. Brassolis granadensis male, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 4,5. Brassolis isthmia isthmia female, PANAMÁ: Taboga Island, BMNH. 6. Brassolis isthmia isthmia Lectotype male, PANAMÁ: Lion Hill, BMNH. 7,8. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype female, COLOMBIA: Chaparral, ICNO. 9. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype male, COLOMBIA: Mariquita, UPI. 10,11. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype female, ECUADOR: Tinalandia, CRB. 12. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype male, ECUADOR: Balzapamba (Paralectotype male of Brassolis granadensis), BMNH. 13. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 14. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 15. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5125059" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5125059/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Plate 3</figureCitation>
, fig. 4) and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Racheli and Racheli" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[1284,1393,626,651]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sophorae">
<emphasis box="[1284,1393,626,651]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">sophorae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are either absent (as in all nominate 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stichel. The" authorityYear="1902" box="[531,635,666,691]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haenschi">
<emphasis box="[531,635,666,691]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">haenschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
examined), or represented by just one (never two) indistinct line (as in a female 
<emphasis box="[298,409,706,731]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">rufescens</emphasis>
from Huancabamba and 
<specimenCount box="[717,827,706,732]" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" type="male">one male</specimenCount>
<emphasis box="[837,956,706,731]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">maritimus</emphasis>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[1034,1160,706,732]" name="Venezuela" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
). These two characters appear to be defining features of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stichel. The" authorityYear="1902" box="[538,642,746,771]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haenschi">
<emphasis box="[538,642,746,771]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">haenschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[657,741,746,772]" captionStart="PLATE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,238,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-116@9.[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="PLATE 3 (details). 1,2. Brassolis granadensis female, COLOMBIA: Otanche, JFL. 3. Brassolis granadensis male, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 4,5. Brassolis isthmia isthmia female, PANAMÁ: Taboga Island, BMNH. 6. Brassolis isthmia isthmia Lectotype male, PANAMÁ: Lion Hill, BMNH. 7,8. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype female, COLOMBIA: Chaparral, ICNO. 9. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype male, COLOMBIA: Mariquita, UPI. 10,11. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype female, ECUADOR: Tinalandia, CRB. 12. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype male, ECUADOR: Balzapamba (Paralectotype male of Brassolis granadensis), BMNH. 13. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 14. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 15. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5125059" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5125059/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Plate 3</figureCitation>
, figs. 13&amp;14).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="57" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,266,1092]" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">
The forewing band of nominate 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stichel. The" authorityYear="1902" box="[578,682,786,811]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Brassolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haenschi">
<emphasis box="[578,682,786,811]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">haenschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has an almost white ‘highlight’ close to the cell and costal margin (
<figureCitation box="[203,287,826,852]" captionStart="PLATE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,238,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-116@9.[226,1360,194,1740]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="PLATE 3 (details). 1,2. Brassolis granadensis female, COLOMBIA: Otanche, JFL. 3. Brassolis granadensis male, COLOMBIA: Río Magdalena, BMNH. 4,5. Brassolis isthmia isthmia female, PANAMÁ: Taboga Island, BMNH. 6. Brassolis isthmia isthmia Lectotype male, PANAMÁ: Lion Hill, BMNH. 7,8. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype female, COLOMBIA: Chaparral, ICNO. 9. Brassolis isthmia daisye Paratype male, COLOMBIA: Mariquita, UPI. 10,11. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype female, ECUADOR: Tinalandia, CRB. 12. Brassolis isthmia wallengreni Paratype male, ECUADOR: Balzapamba (Paralectotype male of Brassolis granadensis), BMNH. 13. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 14. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC. 15. Brassolis haenschi haenschi male ECUADOR: Macas, ZMUC." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5125059" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5125059/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="57">Plate 3</figureCitation>
, fig. 15); on the hindwing, there is just a very faint, apically developed, sub-marginal band. In the female, there is no sub-marginal hindwing band; the forewing band is a deep orange and composed of a series of touching spots. Where these cross the upper part of the cell, they are elongated distally into ‘flame-like’ spots. On the underside, the outer ocellus on the hindwing does not have an inner, dark brown circle.
</paragraph>
